Venezuela
---
[5] Orinoco Delta
Date: Sat 13 Jan 2018
Source: [in Spanish, trans., edited]
http://www.correodelcaroni.com/index.php/mas/salud/item/61730-reportan-casos-de-tos-ferina-en-comunidad-warao-del-delta-del-orinoco


The Warao community of Bonoina, located in the Orinoco canals, in Delta Amacuro, reports an approximate of 10 whooping cough infections in children and adults. "It's a suffocating cough and the problem is that in dispensaries there are medicines," said Trino Ávila, a resident of the town.

Ávila pointed out that they have not yet been confirmed by the State in the absence of specialists the Orinoco Delta. His family is one of those affected by the recent illness. "I didn't know what to do, without medicines, far from the city, isolated in these rivers ...desperation takes over one," he lamented.

Ancestral knowledge came to pass and a wise Warao recommended that he bury a dry coconut filled with brown sugar and place a burning stove over it all night long. When unearthing it, there is a syrup, product of the mixture of both ingredients, and with that he cured his children.

[...]

A total of 25 000 Waraos live in the Antonio Díaz municipality of Delta Amacuro, hidden between canals, islands, and mangroves of the Orinoco River that flow into the Atlantic Ocean and the Caribbean Sea. They survive from agriculture and fisheries, in the absence of basic state services and now face an epidemic of whooping cough.

[Byline: Oriana Faoro]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Orinoco Delta is one of the 8 natural regions of Venezuela and it covers the whole of Delta Amacuro state and a few square kilometers of Monagas state and Sucre state, comprising all the mouths of the Orinoco (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orinoco_Delta). A map of this region can be found at http://www.exploremargarita.com/maps/map_delta.htm. The Warao are an indigenous people inhabiting northeastern Venezuela, Trinidad and Tobago, Guyana, and Suriname, with a lifelong and intimate connection to the water; most of the approximately 20 000 Warao inhabit Venezuela's Orinoco Delta region (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warao_people). - Mod.ML

HealthMap/ProMED-mail map
Orinoco Delta, Delta Amacuro, Venezuela: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5597154,63687]

